h the world. In the first half of the book, Kochman addresses white men, explicating the ways that their cultural background can motivate their behavior, work style, and perspective on others. Then Mavrelis turns to white women, focusing on the particular problems they face, including conflicts with men, other women, and themselves. Together they emphasize the need for a multicultural—rather than homogenizing—approach and offer constructive ideas for turning the workplace into a more interactive community for everyone who works there. Written with the wisdom and clarity gained from two decades of hands-on work, Corporate Tribalism will be an invaluable resource as we look toward a future beyond the glass ceiling.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCultural awareness. 0aDiversity in the workplace. 0aIntercultural communication. 0aWhite peoplexAttitudes. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  atribal, white, race, racism, male, female, gender, culture, cultural, diverse, diversity, workplace, workforce, labor, professional, career, worker, election, 2008, 21st century, barack obama, politics, political, precedent, hillary clinton, sarah palin, corporate, america, american, united states, usa, miscommunication, bias, glass ceiling, networking.1 aMavrelis, Jean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022644957940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226449593423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226449593/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP